<DOC><DOCNO> WSJ880113-0010 </DOCNO><HL> Texas Instruments Gets $499.3 Million For Navy Missile Job </HL><SO> </SO><CO> TXN GD CSC GM GMH GQ KAMNA </CO><IN> ARO </IN><G> DEF </G><DATELINE> WASHINGTON  </DATELINE><TEXT>   Texas Instruments Inc. got a $499.3 million Navy contract to produce high-speed anti-radiation missiles.    The contract will provide 773 missiles for the Navy, 1,475 for the Air Force and 180 for West Germany. Work is to be completed by December 1990.    The Electric Boat Division of General Dynamics Corp. received a $152.7 million Navy contract for ballistic-missile submarine engineering services.    Computer Sciences Corp. said it received a $116 million Air Force contract to provide engineering and technical services for flight tests. The contract includes options that would raise the total value to $278 million, the company said.    Hughes Aircraft Co., a unit of General Motors Corp., was awarded a $16.9 million Navy contract for weapon-delivery equipment for AV-8B aircraft.    American Apparel Co. got a $15 million Defense Logistics Agency contract for combat coats.    Grumman Corp. was given Navy contracts totaling $14.7 million for F-14 aircraft-communications improvements and A-6 aircraft program services.    Kaman Corp. won a $10.8 million Navy contract for SH-2F helicopter improvements. </TEXT></DOC>